{"title_page": "Morris Babyface", "text_new": "Marx Morris Twumasi (born 21st January,1980), known as Morris Babyface is a [[Ghana|Ghanaian]] [[Music]] [[Record producer|Producer]], [[singer]] and [[songwriter]] who hails from the [[Ashanti Region]] of Ghana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djsinafrica.com/morris-babyface/|title=Morris Babyface|date=2020-04-02|website=DJs In Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/music/201001/37351.php|title=Morris Babyface Shoots \ufffdValentine\ufffd Video|last=Online|first=Peace FM|website=www.peacefmonline.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201608191263.html|title=Ghana: Technology Has Made Producers Lazy - Morris Babyface|last=|first=|date=|website=AllAfrica|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Morris is known to have recorded most prominent artist in Ghana with the likes of Pat Thomas, [[Kojo Antwi]], [[Ofori Amponsah]], [[A. B. Crentsil|A. B. Crentstil]], [[Kontihene]], Okomfoo Kwadee, [[Esther Smith (singer)|Esther Smith]], etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydjlive.com/god-forgive-you-morris-babyface-tells-wiyaala/|title=\"God forgive you\" - Morris BabyFace tells Wiyaala|date=2015-05-01|website=NYDJ Live|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bigtimerz.com/entertainment/morris-babyface-finally-finds-lost-okomfour-kwadee-any-new-music-yet-find-out-the-twists-and-turns|title=Morris Babyface finally finds \u2018lost\u2019 Okomfour Kwadee {{!}} Any new music yet? Find out the twists and turns|last=Maclean|first=George Awiadem|website=Bigtimerz|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Life and Career ==\nMorris Babyface was born to the native palm-wine guitarist Kofi Twumasi of the Koo Nimo and his Adadammu fame. He has won the Ghana Music Awards' Best sound engineer twice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djsinafrica.com/morris-babyface/|title=Morris Babyface|date=2020-04-02|website=DJs In Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/music/201001/37351.php|title=Morris Babyface Shoots \ufffdValentine\ufffd Video|last=Online|first=Peace FM|website=www.peacefmonline.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Ghana-stub}}\n", "text_old": "Marx Morris Twumasi (born 21st January,1980), known as Morris Babyface is a [[Ghana|Ghanaian]] [[Music]] [[Producer]], [[singer]] and [[songwriter]] who hails from the [[Ashanti Region]] of Ghana.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djsinafrica.com/morris-babyface/|title=Morris Babyface|date=2020-04-02|website=DJs In Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/music/201001/37351.php|title=Morris Babyface Shoots \ufffdValentine\ufffd Video|last=Online|first=Peace FM|website=www.peacefmonline.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/201608191263.html|title=Ghana: Technology Has Made Producers Lazy - Morris Babyface|last=|first=|date=|website=AllAfrica|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref> Morris is known to have recorded most prominent artist in Ghana with the likes of Pat Thomas, [[Kojo Antwi]], [[Ofori Amponsah]], [[A. B. Crentsil|A. B. Crentstil]], [[Kontihene]], Okomfoo Kwadee, [[Esther Smith (singer)|Esther Smith]], etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydjlive.com/god-forgive-you-morris-babyface-tells-wiyaala/|title=\"God forgive you\" - Morris BabyFace tells Wiyaala|date=2015-05-01|website=NYDJ Live|language=en-GB|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bigtimerz.com/entertainment/morris-babyface-finally-finds-lost-okomfour-kwadee-any-new-music-yet-find-out-the-twists-and-turns|title=Morris Babyface finally finds \u2018lost\u2019 Okomfour Kwadee {{!}} Any new music yet? Find out the twists and turns|last=Maclean|first=George Awiadem|website=Bigtimerz|language=en-gb|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== Life and Career ==\nMorris Babyface was born to the native palm-wine guitarist Kofi Twumasi of the Koo Nimo and his Adadammu fame. He has won the Ghana Music Awards' Best sound engineer twice.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djsinafrica.com/morris-babyface/|title=Morris Babyface|date=2020-04-02|website=DJs In Africa|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.peacefmonline.com/pages/showbiz/music/201001/37351.php|title=Morris Babyface Shoots \ufffdValentine\ufffd Video|last=Online|first=Peace FM|website=www.peacefmonline.com|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n[[Category:Ghanaian producers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n\n{{Ghana-bio-stub}}\n{{Ghana-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toProducer(link changed toRecord producer) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Morris_Babyface"}
{"title_page": "Shou-Chuan Lee", "text_new": "'''Shou-Chuan Lee''' (born 29 April 1955) is from Ruifang, [[Taiwan]]. He graduated from Feng Chia University with an undergraduate degree in [[Economics]]. Lee is a [[Record producer|producer]], A&R, [[songwriter]], and Taiwan folk songs activist in the Taiwanese music industry.\n\n== Career ==\n\n=== Early career ===\nLee began to perform as early as his college years when he played the guitar and worked as DJ at pubs. He then came to acquaintance with the boss of Taichung's Sunrise Bistro, Stone Chang, whom became the lyricist of \u201cThe Song of Chang San \u5f35\u4e09\u7684\u6b4c\u201d (theme song for the 1986 movie \u201cThe Two of Us \u7236\u5b50\u95dc\u4fc2\u201d, also a song in the album \u201c8 and \u00bd 8\u53c8\u4e8c\u5206\u4e4b\u4e00\u201d).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029223837/http://tw.myblog.yahoo.com/jw!SObM4miRGBjTW1Z4PZeF_GYj/article?mid=3|title=[\u5f35\u4e09\u7684\u6b4c]\u4f5c\u8a5e\u66f2\u4eba\u5f35\u5b50\u77f3\u4e4b\u6700\u5f8c\u907a\u4f5c - \u97f3\u6a02\u8001\u5e2b\u4f5c\u66f2\u5bb6 - Yahoo!\u5947\u6469\u90e8\u843d\u683c|date=2013-10-29|website=web.archive.org|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\u00a0 After serving the military, Lee entered Synco Cultural Corporation as a producer, and worked with Chih-yuan Chen on Jian Fu Li's first album \u201cDescendants of the Dragon \u9f8d\u7684\u50b3\u4eba\u201d, marking a new height in the Taiwanese folk songs era.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://nrch.culture.tw/twpedia.aspx?id=10207|title=\u6587\u5316\u90e8\u53f0\u7063\u5927\u767e\u79d1\u5168\u66f8|last=|first=|date=|website=nrch.culture.tw|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Songwriter and Producer ===\nUpon his first production, Jian Fu Li's \u201cDescendants of the Dragon \u9f8d\u7684\u50b3\u4eba\u201d, Lee has continued to produce a lot of best-selling albums of the era, such as Michelle Pan's \u201cForever Blue Sky \u5929\u5929\u5929\u85cd\u201d, Julie Sue's \u201cSame Moonlight \u4e00\u6a23\u7684\u6708\u5149\u201d, Chris Hung's \u201cBygone Love is Continuous \u820a\u60c5\u7dbf\u7dbf\u201d, WaWa's \u201cHappy Girl \u958b\u5fc3\u5973\u5b69\u201d, Dave Wong's \u201cOne Game, One Dream \u4e00\u5834\u904a\u6232\u4e00\u5834\u5922\u201d, \u201cForget About You / Forget About Me\u5fd8\u4e86\u4f60\u5fd8\u4e86\u6211\u201d, \u201cThe Role of the Story \u6545\u4e8b\u7684\u89d2\u8272\u201d, Yu-Ching Fei's \u201cGoodnight Song \u665a\u5b89\u66f2\u201d, Leehom Wang's \u201cLove Rival Beethoven \u60c5\u6575\u8c9d\u591a\u82ac\u201d, etc.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://theinitium.com/article/20160920-culture-music-eight-and-ahalf-30th-1/|title=\u8a79\u5b8f\u5fd7\uff1a\u56de\u61b6\u674e\u58fd\u5168\u7684\u300a8\u53c8\u4e8c\u5206\u4e4b\u4e00\u300b|last=|first=|date=|website=theinitium.com|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>  Other than producing record albums, Lee had also participated in movie soundtracks like \u201cPapa, Can You Hear Me Sing? \u642d\u932f\u8eca\u201d and \u201cSuper Citizen \u8d85\u7d1a\u5e02\u6c11\u201d, and has won several Golden Horse Awards for the music he's written.\n\nLee has also contributed his time on developing talents in the music industry and was behind the success of many artists. Not only was he the producer of Julie Sue's soundtrack album \u201cPapa, Can You Hear Me Sing? \u642d\u932f\u8eca\u201d, but also was he the composer of \u201cSame Moonlight \u4e00\u6a23\u7684\u6708\u5149\u201d.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://womany.net/read/article/11789|title=\u91cd\u8b80\u3008\u5f35\u4e09\u7684\u6b4c\u3009\uff01\u99ac\u4e16\u82b3\uff1a\u4e16\u754c\u4e0d\u53ea\u6dd2\u6dbc\uff0c\u9084\u6709\u5149\u4eae\uff5c\u5973\u4eba\u8ff7 Womany|date=2016-09-27|website=womany.net|language=zh-tw|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> At the same time, he inspired Michelle Pan to develop a new voicing which later served as what defined her style.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musttaiwanorg.blogspot.com/2015/08/blog-post_21.html|title=M\u00dcST\u97f3\u6a02\u8457\u4f5c\u5178\u85cf\u8a08\u5283: \u6842\u82b1\u5df7\uff0d \u4e00\u95d5\u77ed\u6b4c\u9053\u76e1\u5f7c\u6642\u9577\u7bc7\u5c0f\u8aaa\u5973\u4eba\u904b\u547d|last=M\u00fcst\u97f3\u6a02\u8457\u4f5c\u5178\u85cf\u8a08\u756b|date=2015-08-21|website=M\u00dcST\u97f3\u6a02\u8457\u4f5c\u5178\u85cf\u8a08\u5283|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>  Other than that, Lee also supported and discovered talents like Dave Wong, David Wong, Leehom Wang, etc. On top of that, when Deserts Chang was in the trouble of her dispute with her record company, Lee also supported her and served as her mentor.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nMoreover, Lee has been showing support for several charity activities with his music. He was the lyricist for the single \u201cTomorrow Will Be Better \u660e\u5929\u6703\u66f4\u597d\u201d in 1985, and the producer for \u201cNature \u5927\u5730\u7684\u7a97\u53e3\u201d, a song welcoming the world renown animal rights activist Jane Goodall visiting Taiwan. Lee's more recent music work on charity have been associated with Buddhist Compassion Relief Tzu Chi Foundation, including the song on environmental issues \u201cYong Yuan De Kali Angke \u6c38\u9060\u7684\u7d05\u6eaa\u6cb3\u201d, the song for Typhoon Morakot's victims \u201cThe Journey of Compassion \u6148\u60b2\u7684\u5fc3\u8def\u201d, and the song for personal development \u201cStudy Jing Si Aphorism \u8b80\u975c\u601d\u8a9e\u201d, etc. Lee is also participating in a fundraising event for AIDS, \u201cTaiwan A+ Love Music Festival in 2019\u201d.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.tzuchi-org.tw/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=4374:2010-10-06-08-43-49&catid=93:culture-project&Itemid=386&lang=zh|title=\u674e\u58fd\u5168 \u97f3\u6a02\u5c55\u73fe\u4eba\u6587\u7cbe\u795e|last=\u6148\u6fdf\u57fa\u91d1\u6703|website=www.tzuchi-org.tw|language=zh-tw|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n=== Solo performances ===\nIn hopes of empowering oneself, and fighting for a fairer royalty scheme, Lee founded the \u201cTian Sui Yue Ji \u5929\u6c34\u6a02\u96c6\u201d Studio with Chin Tsai, Jian Fu Li, Lai Su, Nai Sheng Xu, and Tie Zhang Jin in 1981. Lee initiated and produced two albums with clear themes, \u201cChallah Kohan \u67f4\u62c9\u53ef\u6c57\u201d and \u201cYi Chien Ge Chun Tian \u4e00\u5343\u500b\u6625\u5929\u201d. As a producer himself, Jonathan Lee once expressed that these two albums are classic works that cannot be surpassed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://musttaiwanorg.blogspot.com/2017/04/blog-post.html|title=M\u00dcST\u97f3\u6a02\u8457\u4f5c\u5178\u85cf\u8a08\u5283: \u650f\u4e0a\u6d6a\u75d5\uff0d\u6614\u65e5\u7684\u5275\u4f5c\u8ecc\u8de1|last=M\u00fcst\u97f3\u6a02\u8457\u4f5c\u5178\u85cf\u8a08\u756b|date=2017-04-07|website=M\u00dcST\u97f3\u6a02\u8457\u4f5c\u5178\u85cf\u8a08\u5283|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> Music critic Shi Fang Ma commented that Lee was the first in Taiwan music history to have produced records with album themes in mind. \u201cChallah Kohan \u67f4\u62c9\u53ef\u6c57\u201d did more than just demonstrating the concept of the album, but there were also the orchestral songs that were inspired by the album \u201cCrusader\u201d by Chris de Burgh.\n\nIn 1986, Lee released his solo album \u201c8 and \u00bd 8\u53c8\u4e8c\u5206\u4e4b\u4e00\u201d. He thought folk songs had a really simple music format that was innocent yet the lyrics were too immature. Therefore, Lee wanted to produce an album that can reflect on society issues and start conversations among people.<ref name=\":0\" /> \u00a0 He positioned the album as \u201cliterary rock\u201d, and invited many writers for the lyrics, such as Dachun Zhang, Nien-Jen Wu, Hung-Tze Jan, Ke Hua Chen, etc. The detailed observations and objective criticism these writers were able to present in the lyrics made every song a snapshot of people's daily lives. Lee took his time to think, write, and accumulate his works for the album during the years from 1985 to 1986.<ref name=\":0\" /> The issues that were discussed included the disappointment in morality of men (8 and \u00bd 8\u53c8\u4e8c\u5206\u4e4b\u4e00), crisis of teenagers (Jan Ling Xi Men Ding \u4f54\u9818\u897f\u9580\u753a), hopes and disappointments towards the future (Wei Lai De Wei Lai \u672a\u4f86\u7684\u672a\u4f86), the compassion and sympathy for lower income families (Can Que De Jiao Luo \u6b98\u7f3a\u7684\u89d2\u843d), etc. Of these songs, \u201cJan Ling Xi Men Ding \u4f54\u9818\u897f\u9580\u753a\u201d couldn't get approval from The Government Information Office to broadcast on media. In this song, Lee chanted and sang the prose lyrics, creating a unique voicing that's considered to be of great musical value.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://simplelife.streetvoice.com/post/will_be_rewards_one_day/|title=\u767d\u5ca9\u677e X \u674e\u58fd\u5168\uff1a\u4eca\u5929\u6240\u505a\u7684\u4efb\u4f55\u4e00\u4ef6\u4e8b\u60c5\uff0c\u672a\u4f86\u4e00\u5b9a\u6703\u56de\u5230\u8eab\u4e0a\u3002 {{!}} \u7c21\u55ae\u751f\u6d3b|website=simplelife.streetvoice.com|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n30 years from its original release, Lee re-produced the album \u201c8 and \u00bd 8\u53c8\u4e8c\u5206\u4e4b\u4e00\u201d, inviting those behind the scenes who wrote, recorded, shot photographs for the album to write a few words. He wanted to demonstrate the attitude and seriousness of producing a record album. Lee stated, \u201ca retro version isn\u2019t just screening and then duplicating the album. You still need to create this piece of work devoting your heart and mind.\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://finance.sina.cn/2016-10-14/detail-ifxwvpaq1248482.d.html|title=\u674e\u5bff\u5168\uff1a \u4e00\u9996\u6b4c\u7684\u751f\u547d\u529b\uff0c \u4e09\u5341\u5e74\u540e\u518d\u770b|last=sina_mobile|date=2016-10-14|website=finance.sina.cn|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref> In the history of record sales, \u201c8 and \u00bd 8\u53c8\u4e8c\u5206\u4e4b\u4e00\u201d didn't receive that big of a feedback in terms of revenue, but it's an album that's been spread and appreciated by many musicians and has its significance in the music industry.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hitoradio.com/newweb/5257album|title=Hitoradio\u2027Hit Fm --\u83ef\u4eba\u97f3\u6a02\u5165\u53e3\u6307\u6a19|website=www.hitoradio.com|access-date=2020-02-03}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n\n=== Personal albums ===\n\n* <span class=\"s2\">\u5f35\u4e09\u7684\u6b4c</span>Wei Lai De Wei Lai \u672a\u4f86\u7684\u672a\u4f86, EP (1985) \n* <span class=\"s2\">\u5f35\u4e09\u7684\u6b4c</span>8 and \u00bd 8\u53c8\u4e8c\u5206\u4e4b\u4e00 (1986; 30th anniversary edition in 2016)\n\n=== Movie soundtracks ===\n\n* \u201cPapa, Can You Hear Me Sing? \u642d\u932f\u8eca\u201d (1983)\n* \u201cThe Time You Need A Friend \u7b11\u5320\u201d (1984)\n* \u201cStory of a Bride \u516b\u756a\u5751\u53e3\u7684\u65b0\u5a18\u201d (1985)\n* \u201cSuper Citizen\u00a0 \u8d85\u7d1a\u5e02\u6c11\u201d (1985)\n* \u201cSuper Citizen Ko \u8d85\u7d1a\u5927\u570b\u6c11\u201d (1994)\n\n== Albums produced ==\nListing a few representative works below: \n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|'''\u6b4c\u624b'''\n|'''\u5c08\u8f2f'''\n|-\n|Jian Fu Li\n|\u9f8d\u7684\u50b3\u4eba\u3001\u67f4\u62c9\u53ef\u6c57\u3001\u5938\u7236\u8ffd\u65e5\n|-\n|Jian Fu Li, Chin Tsai\n|\u4e00\u5343\u500b\u6625\u5929\n|-\n|Wen-Cheng Liu\n|\u592a\u967d\u4e00\u6a23\n|-\n|Louie Castro\n|\u967d\u5149\u70ba\u4ec0\u9ebc\u4e0d\u4f86\n|-\n|Michelle Pan\n|\u5929\u5929\u5929\u85cd\u3001\u80ed\u8102\u5317\u6295\u3001\u7121\u8a00\u7684\u6b4c\u3001\u60c5\u5b57\u9019\u689d\u8def\n|-\n|Julie Sue\n|\u300c\u642d\u932f\u8eca\u300d\u96fb\u5f71\u539f\u8072\u5e36\u3001\u8b8a\u5fc3\n|-\n|Chris Hung\n|\u820a\u60c5\u7ef5\u7ef5\n|-\n|Red Ant\n|\u5f9e\u73fe\u5728\u958b\u59cb\n|-\n|Zhao-Mei Tai\n|\u90b0\u8087\u73ab6\n|-\n|David Wu\n|\u51b7\u51b7\u7684\u591c\n|-\n|Vincent Liang\n|\u611f\u89ba\u4e4b\u7d04\n|-\n|Anita Mui\n|\u8513\u73e0\u838e\u83ef\n|-\n|Xiren Tian\n|\u9ede\u71c3\u592a\u967d\n|-\n|WaWa\n|\u958b\u5fc3\u